":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with worsening left leg weakness over six weeks. He has a 10-year history of sciatica following a workplace back injury, usually managed with regular analgesia. Four weeks ago, he recovered from an upper respiratory tract infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and osteoarthritis. His medications include metformin, perindopril, pregabalin, and paracetamol. He works full-time as an office worker and has never required hospitalisation for his back pain. He walks independently without aids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 138/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals reduced power (3/5) in left ankle dorsiflexion and great toe extension, decreased sensation in the L5 dermatome, and an absent left ankle reflex. The right leg is normal. Straight leg raise is positive at 30 degrees on the left. He has normal perianal sensation and anal tone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computed tomography of the lumbar spine","Nerve conduction studies","Lumbar spine X-ray","Magnetic resonance imaging of the lumbar spine","Cerebrospinal fluid analysis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with progressive unilateral neurological deficits in the context of chronic radiculopathy. The key features are worsening left L5 radiculopathy (weakness of ankle dorsiflexion and great toe extension, sensory loss in L5 dermatome, and absent ankle reflex) over six weeks. While there are no features of cauda equina syndrome (normal perianal sensation and anal tone), the progressive nature of symptoms requires urgent investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E of the lumbar spine is the most appropriate next investigation as it provides detailed visualisation of the neural elements, including nerve roots, spinal cord, and surrounding soft tissues. It can identify disc herniation, spinal stenosis, tumours, or other causes of nerve root compression. MRI is particularly important when there are progressive neurological deficits to exclude serious pathology requiring urgent intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E of the lumbar spine can demonstrate bony pathology and some soft tissue changes but has inferior soft tissue resolution compared to MRI. While it may be an alternative if MRI is contraindicated (e.g., non-MRI compatible implants), it is not the first-line investigation for progressive neurological symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E can help differentiate between radiculopathy, plexopathy, and peripheral neuropathy, and may be useful in chronic or stable symptoms. However, they are not the appropriate first investigation when there are progressive neurological deficits that require urgent structural imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar spine X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E can show alignment, degenerative changes, and bony lesions but cannot adequately visualise neural structures or soft tissues. While it may be part of the overall assessment, it is insufficient as the primary investigation for progressive neurological symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebrospinal fluid analysis\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome was suspected, particularly given the recent upper respiratory tract infection. However, the unilateral nature of symptoms, pre-existing spinal pathology, and positive straight leg raise test make a structural cause more likely than an inflammatory polyneuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["New or progressive neurological deficits in patients with known radiculopathy require urgent MRI to exclude cauda equina syndrome.","Recent viral illness may precipitate Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome which can mimic radiculopathy.","Clinical features that suggest cauda equina syndrome include bilateral symptoms, bowel/bladder dysfunction, and saddle anaesthesia."],"references":["Soar H, Comer C, Wilby MJ, Baranidharan G. Lumbar radicular pain. BJA education. 2022 Sep 1;22(9):343-9. Available online at ; https://www.bjaed.org/article/S2058-5349(22)00079-8/fulltext","Dydyk AM, Khan MZ, Singh P. Radicular Back Pain. [Updated 2022 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546593/","McNamee J, Flynn P, O\u0027Leary S, Love M, Kelly B. Imaging in cauda equina syndrome--a pictorial review. Ulster Med J. 2013 May;82(2):100-8. PMID: 24082289; PMCID: PMC3756868. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3756868/","Davis D, Taqi M, Vasudevan A. Sciatica. [Updated 2024 Jan 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507908/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91967"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14648"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91967"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-23T09:37:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-23T09:37:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7341"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109585"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Ne